<p>Not only are these testimonials insanely short, but they come off as fake.</p>
<p>Who is Vicky? And who the hell is Ricky?</p>
<p>You want to use testimonials that describe how your client has benefited from something youâ€™ve helped with. The more detail there is, the more â€œhumanâ€ they are. And the more human, the more believable.</p>
<p>Hereâ€™s a better example (not real):</p>
<p>â€œNot only did WordStream help me overcome my fear of marketing, but they showed me exactly where my advertising dollars were being wasted and which areas were more profitable than others. My business now has a 72% better ROI than before.â€ &#8211; James Van Der Beek, CEO of DawsonsCreekDVDs.com</p>
<p>Note that the full name and business are included, as well details about what kind of results they got with the product/service. Not only is this testimonial more convincing, but it can be used as a reference if your potential customer is still not convinced about doing business with you.</p>
