<p>Youâ€™ll never find one color that makes everyone happy. But youâ€™ll find one that makes the majority happy, and thatâ€™s the one thatâ€™s best for your landing page conversion rates.</p>
<p><strong>SHAPE: </strong>Sometimes, buttons with sharp corners donâ€™t convert as well as ones with rounded corners. Hereâ€™s why:</p>
<ol>
<li>Rounded corners are easier for the eyes and brain to process.</li>
<li>Weâ€™ve been conditioned to be wary of sharp corners, as they can pose a threat. That also applies to buttons (crazy, right?).</li>
<li>Sharp corners also tend to act as arrows, directing attention <em>away</em> from the button and not toward whatâ€™s inside, the <a href="/blog/ws/2010/09/29/unusual-effective-calls-to-action">call to action</a>.</li>
</ol>
<p>Consider, instead of a regular rectangle, square, oval, or round shape, using a combination of shapes. Amazon uses a combination of a circle and a rectangle:</p>
